               <p>The Prosecutor depos'd, That he was robb'd in <placeName id="t17300228-70-crimeloc357">Hampstead-Road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17300228-70-crimeloc357" type="placeName" value="Hampstead-Road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17300228-70-crimeloc357" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17300228-70-off342 t17300228-70-crimeloc357"></join>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17300228-70-off344 t17300228-70-crimeloc357"></join>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17300228-70-off350 t17300228-70-crimeloc357"></join>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17300228-70-off355 t17300228-70-crimeloc357"></join>, near the Halfway-house, about 6 o'Clock in the Morning, the 14th of January last, by 3 Men, and he was positive the Prisoners were 2 of them, and 
               <persName id="t17300228-70-person396">
                  William 
                  Shrimpton 
               <interp inst="t17300228-70-person396" type="surname" value="Shrimpton"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17300228-70-person396" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17300228-70-person396" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             the third; that they were all 3 on Horse-back; that he was going to London with his Goods, that he desiring them not to rob a poor Man, they said, D - n him, they would take his Horse, and all he had; that he not letting go his Horse's Bridle, one of them struck him a Blow on the side of his Face, near the Eye, and made the Fire fly out of it; that they drove away his Horse, Panniers, with Pigs, Spare-ribs, &amp;c. before them; that afterwards hearing at Cheshunt , that 3 Men had been taken up, he went to Weybridge, and there found his Horse,</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17300228-70-person397">
                  William 
                  Shrimpton 
               <interp inst="t17300228-70-person397" type="surname" value="Shrimpton"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17300228-70-person397" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17300228-70-person397" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             depos'd, That on the Wednesday Morning after they had committed the Robbery on Justice Tyson, they went together to Hampsteads, and meeting the Prosecutor near the Half-way-house, they robb'd him, as he had before sworn; that Ferdinando Shrimpton, drove the Prosecutor's Horse so fast before him, that the Panniers turn'd round under the Horse's Belly; that they took out the Pigs, and Pork, and left the Panniers in the Road, and Drummond rode the Prosecutor's Horse, till they were taken at Weybridge.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17300228-70-person398">
                  John 
                  Simonds 
               <interp inst="t17300228-70-person398" type="surname" value="Simonds"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17300228-70-person398" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17300228-70-person398" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             depos'd, That on the 19th of January, about 10 o'Clock in the Morning, he was inform'd that there were 3 suspicious Persons at the Anchor-Inn at Weybridge; that he went and acquainted some Neighbours, and got them to go with him, each of them furnishing himself with Fire-Arms, and other Weapons, and went to the Anchor-Inn; that he went into the Inn-yard, the others standing<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="173002280018"></xptr> at the Gate, and found they had paid their Reckoning ; and were just going away; that he went immediately to the Stable, lock'd the Door, and put the Key in his Pocket; that they came swearing for their Horses; but he told them, they could not have them, before they had given an Account of themselves; that they going into the Room, they were in before, they apprehending them, found 4 Pistols and a Watch, laid in a Corner, that then they carried them before Justice Hopton, with the Pistols and Watch, that they, there giving no good Account of themselves, the Justice committed them to Prison; this Fact being plainly prov'd, the Jury found them <rs id="t17300228-70-verdict358" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17300228-70-verdict358" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               guilty
            </rs> of this Indictment also.</p>
